Performs the §7 cluster-join handshake against <peer-addr> directly over
QUIC. Intended for first-time bootstrap of a not-yet-running node: loads the
active KEK from <data>/keys/0.key and the cluster identity from <data>/cluster.id,
runs Challenge to get a fresh nonce from the peer, computes HMAC-SHA256(KEK, nonce),
and sends Join with the response. The peer's MetaJoinReceiver verifies the response
under its own KEK and admits the node via AddVoter only on match.

Both <data>/keys/0.key and <data>/cluster.id MUST be staged from a healthy peer
before running this command (e.g. `scp peer:<data>/keys/0.key <data>/keys/` and
`scp peer:<data>/cluster.id <data>/`).

For runtime restart-into-join on an already-running node, use `grainfs join` (which
talks to that node's admin UDS).

Example:
  grainfs cluster join 192.168.1.10:7001 \
    --data /var/grainfs/data \
    --node-id node-2 \
    --bind-addr 192.168.1.11:7001 \
    --cluster-key $GRAINFS_CLUSTER_KEY

Usage:
  grainfs cluster join <peer-addr> [flags]

Flags:
      --bind-addr string     raft listen address the joining node will advertise (required)
      --cluster-key string   pre-shared cluster key (required; same as serve --cluster-key)
  -d, --data string          data directory (holds keys/0.key and cluster.id, staged from a healthy peer) (default "./data")
  -h, --help                 help for join
      --node-id string       unique node ID for the joining node (required)
      --timeout duration     join request timeout (default 30s)

Global Flags:
      --endpoint string    admin Unix socket path (required, e.g. ./tmp/admin.sock)
      --format string      Output format: text or json (status/peers/events; ignored elsewhere) (default "text")
      --log-level string   log level: debug, info, warn, error (default "info")
